P43, thank you for sharing this experience.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="18" relname="span"> I have to say, it is fairly typical of the type 
of user involvement (or lack of) in the development process,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="13" relname="span"> particularly when 
applications have to be developed quickly.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="span"> (When are they not, right?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> ho ho).</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="20" relname="span"> It&apos;s good to 
reflect on these things and to think what we could do (better) next time.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="17" relname="span"> Having some 
sense of a visual from the user&apos;s perspective is essential.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="14" relname="span"> This could be done with 
storyboards or even with numerous sticky notes that identify some of the key functions 
and options that the users need.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> It also be just a simple web design to begin to see the 
flow of things.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="antithesis"> This is where the time crunch comes in and prevents user-centered 
development to a certain extent.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="span"> Yet, doing something could save a lot of headaches in 
the end....</segment>
